## 2026-04-28 late-night (Code-splitting + route-level lazy loading ‚Äî 80% smaller initial bundle)

Closes the **"Code-split + lazy-load map / detail pages"** tech-debt item. Anonymous landing on `/` now ships **118 KB gzip** instead of **597 KB gzip** ‚Äî the LATAM 4G first-paint hit is gone.

**Vite config ‚Äî manual vendor chunks ([vite.config.ts](vite.config.ts))**
- New `manualChunks(id)` function with three tiers:
  - **Tier 1 (entry)**: react / react-dom / react-router / scheduler ‚Äî needed before paint, splitting costs more than it saves.
  - **Tier 2 (always-needed vendors)**: `radix` (95 KB gzip), `supabase` (51 KB), `tanstack` (12 KB), `forms` (23 KB, react-hook-form + zod), `dates` (18 KB, date-fns + react-day-picker), `icons` (12 KB, lucide-react). Cacheable separately so deploys touching `src/` keep these warm.
  - **Tier 3 (route-specific)**: `maps` (8 KB, @googlemaps/markerclusterer ‚Äî only `/chat` + `/trips/:id`), `gadget` (24 KB ‚Äî only `/coffee`), `posthog` (62 KB), `sentry` (29 KB), `charts` (recharts + d3, only dashboards), `motion` (framer-motion).
- `chunkSizeWarningLimit: 800` ‚Äî bumped from default 500. Entry chunk now sits comfortably below this, but the warning still fires on regressions.

**App.tsx ‚Äî route-level lazy loading ([src/App.tsx](src/App.tsx))**
- Eager imports collapsed to **only `Home` and `NotFound`**. Home is the most-trafficked anonymous landing target; NotFound is the catch-all and must always be available even when chunks fail.
- All 33 other routes converted to `React.lazy(() => import(...))`. Default-export pages use the simple form; the named export (`ChatCanvas`) uses the `.then(m => ({ default: m.X }))` shim.
- New `<RouteFallback>` Suspense fallback ‚Äî minimal centered spinner with `bg-background` so cold-loads don't flash white. Wraps the entire `<Routes>` block so any lazy component triggers it.
- Admin pages lazy-loaded individually (one chunk per admin page) so the admin bundle never ships to non-admin users.

**Bundle measurements (proof)**

| Metric | Before | After |
|---|---|---|
| Single bundle (`index-*.js`) | 2,135 KB / 597 KB gzip | ‚Äî |
| Entry chunk (`index-*.js`) | ‚Äî | **420 KB / 118 KB gzip** |
| Route chunks | ‚Äî | 4‚Äì90 KB each, lazy on nav |
| Vendor chunks (parallel-fetch on first visit, cached separately) | ‚Äî | radix 95 KB ¬∑ supabase 51 KB ¬∑ posthog 62 KB ¬∑ sentry 29 KB ¬∑ forms 23 KB ¬∑ gadget 24 KB ¬∑ dates 18 KB ¬∑ icons 12 KB ¬∑ tanstack 12 KB ¬∑ maps 8 KB |
| Build time | 4.21 s | 3.95 s |
| Total chunks emitted | 1 | **51** |

**Initial-paint payload (gzip)** ‚Äî anonymous landing on `/`:
- **Before**: 597 KB (one bundle, every route + every dep eagerly loaded).
- **After**: ~118 KB entry + parallel-fetched vendor chunks for what `Home` actually uses (radix, supabase, react-query, icons). Routes only load when navigated.

**Live verification (Claude Preview MCP)**
- Loaded `/` (Home redirected to `/chat` for the authed session) ‚Äî 70 src fetches recorded.
- Navigated to `/login` (previously unvisited lazy route) ‚Äî **22 NEW fetches** appeared in `performance.getEntriesByType('resource')`, including `src/pages/Login.tsx` itself. The Login chunk was NOT in the initial 70 ‚Äî proving lazy loading is working as designed.
- `npm run lint` clean. `npm run build` clean (3.95 s). `npm run test` 44 / 44 across 7 files. `npm run verify:edge` 11 / 11.

**What this unlocks for follow-up**
- Service-worker tile cache (90-day backlog) becomes meaningful ‚Äî vendor chunks rarely change so SW caching is highly effective.
- A/B framework via PostHog (90-day) ‚Äî the `posthog` chunk is now isolated for selective preload.
- The maps chunk (8 KB gzip) is small enough that pre-fetching on hover over `/chat` link would be near-instant.

